## Security Relevance
- RBAC matters for security. Roles control what users can search, edit and administer, which limits unnecessary access and supports least privilege.
- Knowledge objects improve detection and consistency. Event types, tags, lookups and saved searches help standardize how security teams identify and investigate suspicious activity.
- Search and Reporting is central to security monitoring, because analysts use it to search, analyze, and visualize data. Key workspace for identifying anomalies and investigating events.

## SOC Analyst Perspective
- Search and Reporting app is where an analyst spends a lot of time. It is the main place to run searches, review results, and build reports/dashboards from findings.
- Data Summary helps analysts quickly understand available data. Seeing data broken down by host, source, and sourcetype help analyst know where evidence is coming from.
- Search history improves speed and repeatability. Analysts can revisit prior searches, rerun investigations, and refine previous work faster.

## Key Takeaways
- Splunk app organizes Splunk into use-case focused workspaces
- Roles and capabilities control access and actions inside the platform
- Search and Reporting App is the core interface for searching, analyzing, and presenting data
